Here are a few ways to resolve this issue:

### Option 1: Rename One of the Beans
You can rename one of the `corsConfigurationSource` beans to avoid the conflict. For example, you can rename the bean in `WebConfig`:

```java
// In WebConfig.java
@Bean
public CorsConfigurationSource webCorsConfigurationSource() {
    CorsConfiguration configuration = new CorsConfiguration();
    configuration.setAllowedOrigins(Arrays.asList("*"));
    configuration.setAllowedMethods(Arrays.asList("GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE", "OPTIONS"));
    configuration.setAllowedHeaders(Arrays.asList("*"));
    configuration.setAllowCredentials(false);
    configuration.setMaxAge(3600L);

    UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource source = new UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource();
    source.registerCorsConfiguration("/api/**", configuration);

    return source;
}
```

### Option 2: Enable Bean Definition Overriding
If you want to keep both beans with the same name, you can enable bean definition overriding in your `application.properties` or `application.yml`:

```properties
# In application.properties
spring.main.allow-bean-definition-overriding=true
```

```yaml
# In application.yml
spring:
  main:
    allow-bean-definition-overriding: true
```

### Option 3: Consolidate CORS Configuration
If both configurations are meant to achieve the same purpose, consider consolidating them into a single configuration. You can choose one of the classes to define the CORS configuration and remove it from the other.

### Recommended Approach
The best approach depends on your specific requirements. If the CORS configurations are meant to be different, renaming one of the beans is a clean solution. If they are the same, consolidating them into a single configuration is preferable.

